itualist mediums in history, Natale follows the trajectory of spiritualism in Great Britain and the United States from its foundation in 1848 to the beginning of the twentieth century. He demonstrates that spiritualist mediums and leaders adopted many of the promotional strategies and spectacular techniques that were being developed for the broader entertainment industry. Spiritualist mediums were indistinguishable from other professional performers, as they had managers and agents, advertised in the press, and used spectacularism to draw audiences.Addressing the overlap between spiritualism's explosion and nineteenth-century show business, Natale provides an archaeology of how the supernatural became a powerful force in the media and popular culture of today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPopular culturexHistoryx19th centuryxGreat BritainxGreat BritainxUnited States. 0aPopular culturexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPopular culturezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSeancesxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aSeancesxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aSeanceszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSeanceszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSpiritualismxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aSpiritualismxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aSpiritualismzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aSpiritualismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311074524540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271077390423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271077390.jpg  a978-3-11-074524-5  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2